I believe your problem lies in the fact that you are calling both your dispatch function and your props `allSearches`. 

Instead of

    const mapStateToProps = state =&gt; {
      return (
        {
         topSearches: state.topSearchReducer.topSearches,
         allSearches: state.allSearchesReducer.allSearches
        }
      )
    }

Try calling `allSearches` here something else, such as `searches`, for example:

    const mapStateToProps = state =&gt; {
      return {
         topSearches: state.topSearchReducer.topSearches,
         searches: state.allSearchesReducer.allSearches
      };
    };

I tried reproducing your problem here with some dummy data from a testing API:

[![Edit sweet-wescoff-uucmb](https://codesandbox.io/static/img/play-codesandbox.svg)](https://codesandbox.io/s/sweet-wescoff-uucmb?fontsize=14)

In the code, if you change `searches` in the `TopSearches` component back to `allSearches`, you&#39;ll see nothing will happen because now there&#39;s a dispatch function and a props called `allSearches`.

A way to avoid confusion is to create a `mapDispatchToProps`, such as:

    const mapDispatchToProps = dispatch =&gt; {
      return (
        {
         allSearches: () =&gt; dispatch(allSearches())
        }
      )
    }

Then passing in the high order component `connect` like:

    export default connect(
      mapStateToProps,
      mapDispatchToProps
    )(TopSearches);

By doing that, you know right away the `props` that are available in your component and if you have props with the same name.

